WEBVTT

00:01.125 --> 00:03.417
‐ How many times
have y'all been to rehab?

00:03.417 --> 00:05.125
I'm just worried
maybe it doesn't work.

00:05.125 --> 00:06.792
‐ Have you thought about
methadone? It's worth a shot.

00:06.792 --> 00:09.083
‐ The FDA would take action
against OxyContin

00:09.083 --> 00:10.667
if the drug was shown
to be unsafe

00:10.667 --> 00:12.000
when used as prescribed.

00:12.000 --> 00:13.875
‐ You think we'll be shut down
by the higher‐ups?

00:13.875 --> 00:16.125
‐ We start charging individuals
with felonies,

00:16.125 --> 00:17.833
we need the kill shot.

00:17.833 --> 00:18.917
‐ Have you spoken to Curtis?

00:18.917 --> 00:20.417
‐ Is he still
the review officer?

00:20.417 --> 00:21.875
Two years after
the drug hits the market,

00:21.875 --> 00:23.167
Curtis Wright
ends up at Purdue Pharma.

00:23.167 --> 00:24.250
‐ You're kidding me.

00:24.250 --> 00:25.625
‐ "Time Magazine's"
Man of the Year,

00:25.625 --> 00:27.125
Mayor Rudy Giuliani.

00:27.125 --> 00:30.000
‐ I just started a new firm
and I represent Purdue Pharma.

00:30.000 --> 00:31.208
‐ I'm not obsessed with work,

00:31.208 --> 00:33.042
I'm just trying to prevent
mass deaths

00:33.042 --> 00:34.708
from occurring
across the country.

00:34.708 --> 00:36.583
‐ You got any Oxy?
I'm in real bad shape.

00:36.583 --> 00:37.792
I got some H.

00:37.792 --> 00:40.750
It's way cheaper
and it's way better.

00:58.583 --> 01:01.250
Do you,
Arthur Sackler, solemnly swear

01:01.250 --> 01:04.875
the testimony you give
for this Finnix Committee

01:04.875 --> 01:06.458
will be the whole truth

01:06.458 --> 01:09.333
and nothing but the truth,
so help you God?

01:09.333 --> 01:10.917
‐ I do.

01:10.917 --> 01:14.625
The Sackler empire
is completely integrated.

01:14.625 --> 01:18.125
It can devise a new drug
in its development enterprise,

01:18.125 --> 01:20.042
have the drug
clinically tested,

01:20.042 --> 01:23.583
then secure favorable reports
on it from various hospitals

01:23.583 --> 01:25.458
where they have connections.

01:25.458 --> 01:30.875
Your company makes false
and grandiose claims

01:30.875 --> 01:32.667
about products you advertise

01:32.667 --> 01:34.792
using quotes from doctors

01:34.792 --> 01:37.708
that are, in actuality,
on your own payroll,

01:37.708 --> 01:40.333
hidden through a series
of shell companies

01:40.333 --> 01:44.333
you or your family members
secretly control.

01:44.333 --> 01:46.250
‐ Senator, my company

01:46.250 --> 01:50.750
is an ethical pharmaceutical
advertising organization

01:50.750 --> 01:53.083
working in prescription drugs

01:53.083 --> 01:56.208
and materials produced
primarily for physicians.

01:56.208 --> 01:58.542
We continue to operate
on the basis

01:58.542 --> 02:02.333
that good, ethical
pharmaceutical advertising

02:02.333 --> 02:04.042
plays a positive role

02:04.042 --> 02:07.500
in advancing the health
of the community.

02:11.333 --> 02:15.125
I have a very, very high regard
for Purdue Pharma

02:15.125 --> 02:17.208
and its employees
from my district

02:17.208 --> 02:20.417
who work very, very hard
to produce quality products.

02:20.417 --> 02:22.875
Now, the drug OxyContin
has become vital

02:22.875 --> 02:26.375
to people suffering with
chronic and debilitating pain.

02:26.375 --> 02:29.292
Now, let me ask Dr. Van Zee,
and I quote here,

02:29.292 --> 02:33.125
"Conventional wisdom says that
if a drug is widely available,

02:33.125 --> 02:35.708
it will become widely abused."

02:35.708 --> 02:38.000
Is there any more to this
than that?

02:38.000 --> 02:42.000
‐ Senator Dodd,
that is an old medical adage.

02:42.000 --> 02:44.958
‐ One of
those Appalachian things?

02:44.958 --> 02:49.833
‐ Uh, no,
it's a national adage.

02:49.833 --> 02:53.000
I would say by extension,
if you have an abuseable drug

02:53.000 --> 02:57.792
that is widely available,
it will be widely abused.

02:57.792 --> 03:00.208
In the 25 years
I have practiced medicine

03:00.208 --> 03:02.292
in my small Appalachian town,

03:02.292 --> 03:04.708
there has never been anything
to compare

03:04.708 --> 03:08.542
to the epidemic of drug abuse
and addiction like OxyContin.

03:22.000 --> 03:23.583
‐ If you see this girl,

03:23.583 --> 03:25.542
just give a call
at that number below.

03:25.542 --> 03:27.042
There's a reward.

03:27.042 --> 03:28.333
Excuse me.

03:28.333 --> 03:30.958
I'm trying to find my daughter,
Betsy Mallum.

03:30.958 --> 03:31.958
Have you seen her?

03:33.750 --> 03:38.458
Please, tell her we're not mad,
we're just real worried.

03:43.583 --> 03:45.458
‐ I know where she is.

04:02.250 --> 04:04.750
‐ Betsy.

04:04.750 --> 04:06.375
Betsy.

04:06.375 --> 04:10.333
Betsy, Betsy.
It's Mama.

04:10.333 --> 04:12.208
‐ Hon.
‐ Mom.

04:12.208 --> 04:17.167
I'm here, I'm here.
Betsy?

04:17.167 --> 04:19.250
‐ I want to go home.
‐ Okay.

04:22.000 --> 04:23.875
I never hated myself more

04:23.875 --> 04:26.792
than when I agreed
to get arrest reports.

04:26.792 --> 04:29.083
Some of my former patients.

04:29.083 --> 04:32.875
Some of them I had delivered
as babies.

04:32.875 --> 04:34.458
The shame
and the guilt I felt‐‐

04:34.458 --> 04:35.542
‐ Okay, you know what,

04:35.542 --> 04:38.250
I'm gonna stop you
right there, Sam.

04:38.250 --> 04:40.667
Sam, can you tell me
how many babies you delivered

04:40.667 --> 04:41.708
over the years?

04:41.708 --> 04:44.250
‐ 214.

04:44.250 --> 04:46.750
‐ 214, wow.
‐ Yep, 214.

04:46.750 --> 04:48.833
In those days, you know,
you had to do it all.

04:48.833 --> 04:50.333
‐ Well,
that must've been wonderful.

04:50.333 --> 04:51.958
‐ Yeah.
Right?

04:51.958 --> 04:55.542
Helping all those parents?
All the pain and anxiety?

04:55.542 --> 04:56.583
‐ Yeah.

04:56.583 --> 04:58.542
Delivering their children.

04:58.542 --> 05:02.708
And unlike most city doctors,

05:02.708 --> 05:04.833
you get to watch them grow up.

05:04.833 --> 05:06.833
‐ Yep.
Yep.

05:06.833 --> 05:08.750
‐ Uh‐huh.

05:08.750 --> 05:11.292
‐ You've made some mistakes.

05:11.292 --> 05:14.208
But you've done
some wonderful things, too.

05:16.958 --> 05:19.167
Next session,
I want you to journal about,

05:19.167 --> 05:23.792
uh, what it feels like
to deliver a baby.

05:23.792 --> 05:25.333
Yeah?

05:25.333 --> 05:29.000
And I want you to focus on the
positive things that you did.

05:29.000 --> 05:32.042
We already know
about all your regrets.

05:32.042 --> 05:34.375
I want to hear
about these births.

05:39.292 --> 05:40.292
Samuel?

05:40.292 --> 05:41.542
‐ Yeah.

05:52.583 --> 05:55.042
The Sackler Center
for Arts Education

05:55.042 --> 05:57.000
is one of the most
satisfying things

05:57.000 --> 05:58.500
that our family
has been part of.

05:58.500 --> 05:59.875
I want to thank my brother,
Raymond,

05:59.875 --> 06:02.958
for being here tonight
to celebrate the great work

06:02.958 --> 06:05.375
and the next generation
of artists.

06:06.750 --> 06:10.708
‐ What's the status
with the children's OxyContin?

06:10.708 --> 06:14.208
‐ Still in development,
but coming along nicely.

06:14.208 --> 06:15.500
‐ Hey, cuz.

06:15.500 --> 06:17.583
Hey, congratulations
on another great year.

06:17.583 --> 06:20.042
Sales keep going up.

06:20.042 --> 06:22.167
Yes, David, it's going well.

06:22.167 --> 06:25.792
‐ So a few of us were thinking
of buying a ski resort company.

06:25.792 --> 06:28.000
They've got amazing slopes
all over the country.

06:28.000 --> 06:29.250
And I know how much
you love to ski, so‐‐

06:29.250 --> 06:30.792
‐ Excuse me.

06:30.792 --> 06:34.667
I‐‐I‐‐I have to take this, but
yes, yes, I'm very interested.

06:37.792 --> 06:41.208
Curtis?
Tell me.

06:41.208 --> 06:44.000
It's bad, Dr. Richards.

06:44.000 --> 06:46.333
My intel is from
inside the FDA

06:46.333 --> 06:47.542
and they plan on reviewing

06:47.542 --> 06:49.792
the wording
of the OxyContin label.

06:49.792 --> 06:51.792
And it's very likely
they're gonna change it.

06:51.792 --> 06:53.708
‐ Fuck.
‐ Oh, my God.

06:53.708 --> 06:55.792
‐ But why would the FDA

06:55.792 --> 06:58.667
change our warning label
out of the blue?

06:58.667 --> 07:00.708
‐ Oh, please.
‐ That's enough.

07:00.708 --> 07:02.333
‐ Your son is the only one

07:02.333 --> 07:06.333
unaware that his drug
is a national punching bag.

07:06.333 --> 07:09.583
‐ God damn it, Curtis,
we brought you in from the FDA

07:09.583 --> 07:12.667
to make sure things like this
didn't happen.

07:12.667 --> 07:14.667
‐ That's right.
‐ Look, look, Rich.

07:14.667 --> 07:16.250
Dr. Richard.

07:16.250 --> 07:18.417
The press war
that woman at the DEA started

07:18.417 --> 07:19.792
has had some effect.

07:19.792 --> 07:22.125
There's just too much
bad publicity about the drug

07:22.125 --> 07:24.458
and the FDA
needs to take action.

07:24.458 --> 07:26.958
‐ Curtis, are there
any concessions we can offer

07:26.958 --> 07:28.917
that will prevent them
from changing the label?

07:28.917 --> 07:30.167
‐ Here's an idea.

07:30.167 --> 07:32.083
What if we tell them
we'll pull the 160?

07:32.083 --> 07:34.708
‐ We have invested‐‐
‐ We can try.

07:34.708 --> 07:37.625
‐ But I think our best bet
is to see if we can work out

07:37.625 --> 07:39.375
new language with them.

07:39.375 --> 07:41.042
L‐like the first time.

07:41.042 --> 07:42.583
The wording may
not be as beneficial,

07:42.583 --> 07:44.917
but hopefully
will minimize the damage.

07:44.917 --> 07:47.833
‐ If we have to give up
"addiction is rare,"

07:47.833 --> 07:49.083
sales will plummet.

07:49.083 --> 07:51.792
‐ Let's send a delegation
to meet with the FDA.

07:51.792 --> 07:54.583
I'm sure there are ways
we can aid them

07:54.583 --> 07:57.083
in rewriting this new label.

08:03.292 --> 08:05.708
‐ The good news is
the misbranding case

08:05.708 --> 08:07.000
is open and shut.

08:07.000 --> 08:09.125
Everything we've compiled shows

08:09.125 --> 08:12.000
that Purdue systemically
oversold the benefits

08:12.000 --> 08:13.917
and trivialized
the risks of OxyContin.

08:13.917 --> 08:15.875
But it doesn't put us
over the finish line

08:15.875 --> 08:19.083
'cause we still haven't
charged individuals at the top,

08:19.083 --> 08:21.042
and putting executives
into jail

08:21.042 --> 08:23.583
is truly the most effective way

08:23.583 --> 08:25.958
of deterring companies
from this type of behavior.

08:25.958 --> 08:28.708
‐ You can fine a company,
but you can't put it in jail.

08:28.708 --> 08:31.167
‐ Because a company
feels no pain.

08:31.167 --> 08:33.500
I want Purdue
to feel some pain,

08:33.500 --> 08:35.417
so let's make a final push.

08:35.417 --> 08:36.625
Let's shake every tree.

08:36.625 --> 08:39.500
Financial records, call notes,

08:39.500 --> 08:41.625
applications,
marketing materials.

08:41.625 --> 08:43.708
See if we can find
some hard evidence

08:43.708 --> 08:45.542
against top executives.

08:45.542 --> 08:47.583
Let's go out there and do it.
All right.

08:50.667 --> 08:52.708
Morning, Ms. Moles.

08:52.708 --> 08:55.792
It's Randy Ramseyer, U.S.
Attorney's Office Abingdon.

08:55.792 --> 08:57.417
We talked about four years ago.

08:57.417 --> 08:59.417
‐ Sorry, I'm late for work.

08:59.417 --> 09:02.083
‐ Oh, should we talk
at the FDA instead?

09:02.083 --> 09:04.625
I had a couple questions
about Curtis Wright,

09:04.625 --> 09:08.708
specifically the OxyContin
label that he approved.

09:08.708 --> 09:09.958
You know, actually,

09:09.958 --> 09:12.167
we got a bunch
of unanswered questions

09:12.167 --> 09:14.125
and we're not afraid
to open up our investigation

09:14.125 --> 09:15.833
to individuals
beyond Curtis Wright.

09:15.833 --> 09:16.958
‐ You're referring to me?

09:16.958 --> 09:18.583
‐ I'm referring to anybody
at the FDA

09:18.583 --> 09:21.167
who played a part in that
approval process, ma'am.

09:21.167 --> 09:24.417
We got Purdue sales reps
using that warning label

09:24.417 --> 09:27.750
to sell OxyContin
as basically nonaddictive.

09:27.750 --> 09:30.333
And the guy that approved it
went from working at the FDA

09:30.333 --> 09:34.458
to working for Purdue Pharma
for $379,000 a year.

09:34.458 --> 09:36.625
I mean, it looks to me like

09:36.625 --> 09:38.625
he sold out the health
of the nation.

09:38.625 --> 09:39.958
And I just need to know

09:39.958 --> 09:42.083
if he was promised a job
for that approval.

09:42.083 --> 09:45.000
‐ I have no idea.
I wasn't part of that process.

09:45.000 --> 09:46.375
Now, I have to go to work.

09:50.167 --> 09:51.833
‐ A few years ago,
I had cancer.

09:51.833 --> 09:54.042
And I'm fine now,
but at the time,

09:54.042 --> 09:55.458
when I was in the hospital,

09:55.458 --> 09:58.458
well, I very easily could've
become addicted to Oxy.

09:58.458 --> 10:00.500
And it wouldn't have been
the disease that killed me,

10:00.500 --> 10:02.250
it would've been my medication.

10:04.500 --> 10:05.625
I got lucky.

10:05.625 --> 10:06.625
I just want you to think
of all the kids

10:06.625 --> 10:08.292
that are not getting lucky.

10:11.417 --> 10:13.542
‐ My, uh,
neighbor's kid got hooked.

10:15.500 --> 10:18.375
‐ Please just tell me what you
know about that warning label.

10:18.375 --> 10:20.958
We both know there's
something rotten going on here.

10:23.625 --> 10:26.958
‐ I heard that

10:26.958 --> 10:29.917
about a year
before the drug was approved,

10:29.917 --> 10:33.208
Purdue rented out a hotel suite
in Rockville

10:33.208 --> 10:34.500
down the road from the FDA,

10:34.500 --> 10:37.667
where they meet
with Curtis Wright in private.

10:37.667 --> 10:40.500
Supposedly, Curtis
and the Purdue executives

10:40.500 --> 10:42.958
spent three days together,

10:42.958 --> 10:45.917
working out the wording
of the medical review,

10:45.917 --> 10:48.542
co‐writing the summary
of safety and efficacy.

10:48.542 --> 10:50.125
An FDA employee

10:50.125 --> 10:54.292
literally helped Purdue
write their own review.

10:54.292 --> 10:57.958
‐ Did Curtis Wright pen
the OxyContin warning label

10:57.958 --> 11:00.250
for Purdue?
Did‐‐

11:00.250 --> 11:02.042
did he actually write it?

11:02.042 --> 11:06.167
‐ There is more than one person
that believes that he did.

11:06.167 --> 11:08.917
‐ Do you know who from Purdue
was in that hotel room

11:08.917 --> 11:11.042
with Curtis Wright?
Was it‐‐

11:11.042 --> 11:12.625
was it senior‐level executives?

11:12.625 --> 11:14.750
‐ I'm sorry,
I honestly don't know.

11:14.750 --> 11:18.333
Because if I did,
I would tell you.

11:18.333 --> 11:21.083
Got to go to work.

11:21.083 --> 11:23.333
‐ Have you told any of this
to anybody else before?

11:23.333 --> 11:25.125
No.

11:25.125 --> 11:26.250
‐ Why not?

11:26.250 --> 11:28.042
‐ 'Cause it wouldn't matter
if I did.

11:42.375 --> 11:45.958
There's these flyers
all over town.

11:45.958 --> 11:48.875
A big meeting tomorrow night.

11:48.875 --> 11:52.000
About OxyContin, hmm?
I think we should go.

11:53.417 --> 11:56.250
‐ I don't want people
to see me there.

11:56.250 --> 11:57.708
Then they'll know, Mom.
No.

11:57.708 --> 11:59.667
‐ I don't care what they know.

11:59.667 --> 12:01.958
There might be
some helpful information.

12:01.958 --> 12:05.292
We got to find a way
to get you better, honey.

12:05.292 --> 12:08.625
The real you is still in there.
I just know it.

12:13.208 --> 12:14.792
‐ I don't know
where she's gone.

12:14.792 --> 12:18.292
‐ Well, we got to
find her again, then.

12:18.292 --> 12:19.875
Well?

12:23.917 --> 12:25.917
‐ Okay, Mama.
Okay.

12:37.083 --> 12:38.625
‐ What you got there?

12:41.375 --> 12:44.625
‐ It's for a meeting
about all these drugs.

12:44.625 --> 12:46.167
I know what you're gonna say,

12:46.167 --> 12:48.792
but I don't care
if people know our business.

12:48.792 --> 12:52.250
There's nothing that you
can say to keep me from going.

12:52.250 --> 12:56.583
‐ I‐‐I don't want to stop you
from doing anything, Diane.

12:56.583 --> 12:59.542
You do whatever you need to do.

13:03.542 --> 13:06.958
‐ My name
is Sister Beth Davies.

13:06.958 --> 13:09.792
I want to thank you all
for coming down here.

13:09.792 --> 13:13.083
It's not easy,
as so many of you

13:13.083 --> 13:15.875
are carrying the heavy burden
of a loved one

13:15.875 --> 13:20.292
suffering from this
chronic disease of addiction.

13:20.292 --> 13:22.625
With that said,
I want to introduce you

13:22.625 --> 13:26.792
to the most dedicated
recovery doctor in Appalachia,

13:26.792 --> 13:29.333
Dr. Art Van Zee.

13:33.292 --> 13:35.875
‐ Thank you, Sister Beth.

13:35.875 --> 13:39.375
I know it wasn't easy
for you all to come tonight,

13:39.375 --> 13:42.125
as this addiction
has shame attached to it,

13:42.125 --> 13:46.042
but I hope you all see by this
turnout that you're not alone.

13:46.042 --> 13:49.417
This drug doesn't care
if you're rich or poor,

13:49.417 --> 13:52.417
man or woman,
white, Black, or brown.

13:52.417 --> 13:56.208
Once you've taken too much,
it changes your brain chemistry

13:56.208 --> 13:58.333
so you're in so much pain
without it,

13:58.333 --> 14:01.208
you think you're going to die.

14:01.208 --> 14:03.958
I brought you here tonight
to sign a petition

14:03.958 --> 14:07.208
to ask the FDA to
pull OxyContin from the market

14:07.208 --> 14:11.625
till it can be reformulated
to be resistant to abuse.

14:11.625 --> 14:13.500
It's been done before.

14:13.500 --> 14:16.500
So, after the meeting,
we have tables set up over here

14:16.500 --> 14:18.583
for you
all to sign the petition

14:18.583 --> 14:22.167
so we can try to bring an end
to this nightmare.

14:53.667 --> 14:54.917
I couldn't believe
these results

14:54.917 --> 14:56.000
when I first saw them either,
sir.

14:56.000 --> 14:57.958
I mean‐‐and this is rock solid.

14:57.958 --> 15:01.333
See, the autopsy report proves
overdoses can occur in people

15:01.333 --> 15:03.667
who are taking the drug
exactly as prescribed.

15:03.667 --> 15:05.917
It's not just drug abusers
who are dying.

15:05.917 --> 15:09.000
It's everyday
pain patients, too.

15:09.000 --> 15:10.458
‐ You can't just send out
a press release

15:10.458 --> 15:12.333
without discussing this
with the FDA first.

15:12.333 --> 15:15.083
‐ Okay, but, sir, the press war
I orchestrated last year

15:15.083 --> 15:17.042
is what got the FDA
to take action

15:17.042 --> 15:18.292
against Purdue's warning label.

15:18.292 --> 15:21.125
‐ But if you act without
discussing this with us‐‐

15:21.125 --> 15:22.583
‐ Sir,
with all due respect,

15:22.583 --> 15:25.625
the public needs to have access
to this data ASAP

15:25.625 --> 15:27.250
for their own personal safety.

15:27.250 --> 15:29.750
‐ When do you plan on sharing
your report with the FDA?

15:29.750 --> 15:31.583
‐ I've already set up a meeting
next week

15:31.583 --> 15:33.333
and I've requested Purdue
to be there.

15:33.333 --> 15:36.375
‐ Are you giving Purdue the
report ahead of the meeting?

15:36.375 --> 15:37.833
‐ No.

15:37.833 --> 15:39.792
‐ So you're jamming them
into a fast rebuttal

15:39.792 --> 15:42.583
without being able
to review the report first?

15:42.583 --> 15:43.958
‐ Maybe.

15:43.958 --> 15:45.208
‐ You know you're just going
to piss everyone off.

15:45.208 --> 15:47.958
‐ My goal is to stop
a dangerous drug

15:47.958 --> 15:51.208
from being diverted and abused.

15:51.208 --> 15:53.417
I'm not looking
to make friends.

16:08.208 --> 16:09.333
‐ Excuse me.

16:11.042 --> 16:13.500
Uh, if you don't mind.

16:13.500 --> 16:15.875
If you soak that
in some Epsom salts

16:15.875 --> 16:20.167
