or injected the drug.

43:56.042 --> 44:01.167
They had simply swallowed it,
as approved by the FDA.

44:01.167 --> 44:04.458
We know this to be true because
we had photographs of the pills

44:04.458 --> 44:09.125
intact in their stomachs
at the time of autopsy.

44:09.125 --> 44:11.167
‐ It's not possible
to determine

44:11.167 --> 44:12.750
OxyContin‐verified deaths

44:12.750 --> 44:16.208
since the toxicology reports
usually do not list

44:16.208 --> 44:19.625
exact levels of the other drugs
at the time of death.

44:19.625 --> 44:21.792
‐ The DEA marked a death
as OxyContin‐verified

44:21.792 --> 44:24.292
only if the level of OxyContin
in the bloodstream

44:24.292 --> 44:26.917
was high enough to be deadly
on its own.

44:26.917 --> 44:29.625
‐ Assuming the measurements
were accurate,

44:29.625 --> 44:30.625
how do we know that?

44:30.625 --> 44:31.917
‐ Why would they be inaccurate?

44:31.917 --> 44:34.667
The data came directly
from the autopsy reports.

44:34.667 --> 44:36.417
And we only counted
drug combinations

44:36.417 --> 44:38.167
with tranquilizers
and anti‐depressants,

44:38.167 --> 44:40.125
drugs commonly prescribed
with OxyContin

44:40.125 --> 44:41.958
to reduce anxiety
amongst pain patients.

44:41.958 --> 44:43.292
‐ In all likelihood,

44:43.292 --> 44:45.875
we undercounted the number
of OxyContin overdoses

44:45.875 --> 44:48.958
out of an abundance of caution
for accuracy.

44:48.958 --> 44:51.292
‐ Okay, okay.
First of all,

44:51.292 --> 44:54.333
Purdue had not been given
access to this data in advance,

44:54.333 --> 44:56.792
making it impossible for us
to uncover errors

44:56.792 --> 44:58.792
